Prep Patterns
Pattern 1: The 3-Hour Sunday Prep
Full week preparation in one session:
- Hour 1: Season and start proteins (oven + stovetop simultaneously)
- Hour 1.5: Start grains (rice cooker / instant pot) + chop all vegetables
- Hour 2: Roast vegetables, prepare sauces and dressings
- Hour 2.5: Assemble and portion into containers
- Hour 3: Clean up, label, store (fridge for 3 days, freezer for rest)

Pattern 2: Component Prep (Mix-and-Match)
Flexibility over fixed meals:
- Prep 2-3 proteins (grilled chicken, baked fish, cooked lentils)
- Prep 3-4 base grains/starches (rice, quinoa, sweet potato)
- Prep 4-5 vegetables (roasted, steamed, raw salad)
- Prep 2-3 sauces/dressings
- User assembles different combinations through the week

Pattern 3: Budget Warrior Prep
Maximum nutrition on minimum budget:
- Protein anchors: eggs, chicken thighs, canned tuna, lentils, beans
- Carb anchors: rice, oats, potatoes, bread
- Vegetable anchors: frozen vegetables, cabbage, carrots, onions
- Flavor boosters: spices, soy sauce, hot sauce, lemon
- Cost target: under ₹200/day or $5/day per person

Best Practices
Planning
- Plan meals before grocery shopping — never shop without a list
- Overlap ingredients across meals (one chicken for salads, wraps, and stir-fry)
- Keep a rotation of 10-12 proven recipes to reduce decision fatigue
- Prep doesn't mean boring — variety comes from sauces and seasonings
- Start with prepping just lunches — don't try to prep every meal at once

Execution
- Mise en place everything before turning on the stove
- Use parallel cooking: oven proteins + stovetop grains + passive rice cooker
- Cook proteins to temp (use a thermometer), not guesswork
- Let food cool before containerizing to avoid condensation and sogginess
- Label every container with contents and date

Budget
- Buy protein in bulk and freeze in portions
- Frozen vegetables are nutritionally equivalent to fresh and 50% cheaper
- Generic brands for staples (rice, oats, canned goods) — taste is identical
- Track cost-per-meal, target under ₹150-200 or $4-5 per meal
- Waste is the biggest budget killer — eat what you prep

